<h2 id="Irvine">Irvine Ranch Conservancy</h2>
<b>GIS system design and set up, conservation GIS analysis, online GIS library</b>
<p><b>Client:</b> <a href="http://www.irvineranchconservancy.org" target="_blank">Irvine Ranch Conservancy</a></p>
<p><img id="left" src="images/cwren.jpg"> The Irvine Ranch Conservancy is responsible for managing roughly
50,000 acres of open space in Southern California. These lands include
large blocks of increasingly rare Mediterranean habitats such as
coastal sage scrub, oak woodland and riparian forests. A wide variety
of federally listed plants and animals are found in the canyons and
hills that make up the reserve, including California gnatcatcher (<i>Polioptila californica</i>), "Least" Bell's vireo (<i>Vireo bellii</i>), Cactus wren (<i>Campylorhynchus brunneicapillus</i>) and Laguna Beach Dudleya (<i>Dudleya stolonifera</i>).
The reserve also provides abundant recreation opportunities for an
increasingly developed and populous Orange County. Fire, invasive weeds
and illegal access are the chief threats to the reserve.</p>
<p>Simply put, GIS is essential for effective land management and can
be used as a tool to mitigate the threats listed above. My work at the
conservancy involved three related project areas:</p>
<ul>
	<li><b>GIS system design and set up:</b> This involved all
aspects of hardware and software acquisition, data collection from
Irvine Conservancy partners and online repositories and the
establishment of management procedures for data storage and backup.</li>
	<li><b>Conservation GIS analysis:</b> Projects included habitat modeling for a small and highly cute endangered rodent, the Pacific Pocket Mouse (<i>Perognathus longimembris pacificus</i>),
and development of a model to predict the ecological impact of fire
from a 90-year historical fire database. Work continues to field
validate both models.</li>
	<li id="IRC"><b>Online GIS library:</b>
GIS data is only useful if it can be readily and easily put to use. I
developed and implemented a system that documents GIS data using
standard metadata tools, and then uses these metadata records to build
an online searchable database of all GIS data, maps and projects
available at the Conservancy. The resulting GIS "library" is housed
online and accessed via an intuitive web-browser interface. In this way
the library can be searched by any user of the Conservancy's GIS from
anywhere with an internet connection and permission to access the
information. The system was programmed using open source tools including <a href="http://www.rubyonrails.org/">Ruby on Rails</a> to drive a <a href="http://www.mysql.org/">MySQL</a> database. Please email me if you would like to take an inside look.</li>
</ul>
