<h2 id="Madagascar">Madagascar</h2>
<p><b>Clients:</b> <a href="http://www.usaid.gov/missions/mg/">US-AID Madagascar</a>; <a href="http://www.conservation.org/xp/CIWEB/regions/africa/madagascar.xml">Conservation International-Madagascar</a>; <a href="http://www.worldwildlife.org/wildplaces/mad/">WWF-Madagascar</a>.</p>
<p><img id="left" src="images/mad_kids.jpg">Extraordinary levels of endemism and high rates of deforestation
place the Indian Ocean island of Madagascar near the top of virtually
every conservation priority list. Since 2002, I have been working on a
variety of conservation projects in Madagascar, as both an employee of
WWF-US and, more recently, as an independent consultant. Clients have
included WWF-Madagascar and Conservation International-Madagascar. All
projects have involved spatial planning and conservation priority
setting using GIS. Two key projects are highlighted below.</p>
<p><strong>Ecoregion Vision for the Ala Atsinanana (Moist Forest Ecoregion)</strong></p>
<p>The Madagascar Moist Forest Ecoregion, or Ala Atsinanana in
Malagasy, spans nearly two-thirds of the island of Madagascar, covering
over 300,000 km² in total. Though estimates vary, the vast majority of
the ecoregion appears to have once been covered by tropical moist
forest; currently only about 15% remains. The ecoregion is one of WWF's
"Global 200" ecoregions, and as such has become a focus of WWF's
conservation efforts. As part of this, WWF has developed a
"Conservation Vision" for the ecoregion: a 50-year plan for where and
how to achieve effective conservation across the region.</p>
<p>My work on this has involved helping to set and apply the
methodology for delimiting large-scale, long-term priority landscapes
within the ecoregion: the <strong>where</strong> component of the
"vision". This method merged new quantitative methods with classic
expert assessment, drawing on the complimentary strengths of both
approaches. We used the planning software "MARXAN" and other
data-driven methods not to set final, fixed-in-place priorities, but
rather as inputs to support expert delineation of final priority
landscapes. Thus, for perhaps the first time, final priorities were
selected using a combination of expert knowledge and a rigorous,
target-driven analysis incorporating distributional data for hundreds
of species, and utilizing the latest information on forest cover,
deforestation, and other threats.</p>
