<h2 id="Guianas">Guianan Moist Forests</h2>
<p><strong>Clients:</strong> <a href="http://www.wwfguianas.org/">WWF-Guianas</a>; <a href="http://wwf.us/about_wwf/where_we_work/latin_america_and_caribbean/solutions_region/guianas/index.cfm">WWF-US</a>.</p>
<p><img id="left" src="images/gy.jpg">Like the Moist Forests of Madagascar described above, the Guianan
Moist Forests are also a WWF "Global 200" priority ecoregion.
Stretching across almost 550,000 km² of Northeastern South America,
these tropical broadleaf forests, though relatively under-explored, are
amongst the richest in the world in terms of plant and animal species.
Unlike the forests of Madagascar, the Guianan Moist Forests are
relatively undisturbed, in fact close to 90% of the ecoregion remains
in a natural state.</p>
<p>Since 2003, I have been helping WWF-Guianas and local partners
develop a "Conservation Vision" for the Moist Forest ecoregion. This
has involved collecting spatial data for focal species, helping to
produce an ecoregion-wide vegetation classification (pictured below),
developing a GIS and MARXAN-based methodology for identifying and
mapping priority landscapes, and providing GIS trainings for local
staff and partners.</p>
<p>MARXAN has been used to develop a series of potential conservation
scenarios for the ecoregion (see below). Each scenario meets focal
conservation targets and differs in compactness, target levels, and
overall "cost".</p>
